	<section>
		<h2>Overview</h2>
		<p>
			Computer labs in religious institutions, community centers, and libraries serve diverse populations - children doing homework, adults job searching, seniors learning technology, and members accessing resources. Unlike personal devices, public workstations require special management: session limits, content filtering, user isolation, easy reset, and prevention of malware. This guide provides practical strategies for maintaining safe, functional public computers.
		</p>

		<div class="alert alert-info">
			<strong>Key Principle:</strong> Public computers should be "stateless" - each user gets a clean system, and nothing from their session persists to the next user. This prevents malware, protects privacy, and simplifies maintenance.
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>üéØ Management Strategies</h2>

		<div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 my-6">
			<div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border-2 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
				<h3>Strategy 1: Deep Freeze + Filtering Software</h3>
				<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Small labs (5-15 computers), Windows-based</p>
				<h4>How it works:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Deep Freeze "freezes" hard drive - all changes discarded on reboot</li>
					<li>Students can install malware, change settings - gone on restart</li>
					<li>Combine with web filtering software</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Cost:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Deep Freeze: $40/computer one-time</li>
					<li>Filtering software: $20-50/computer/year</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Pros:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Simple, reliable, minimal ongoing maintenance</li>
					<li>Nearly impossible to permanently break</li>
					<li>Works with existing hardware</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Cons:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Updates require "thawing" and re-freezing</li>
					<li>No user profiles or saved work</li>
				</ul>
			</div>

			<div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border-2 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
				<h3>Strategy 2: Active Directory + Group Policy</h3>
				<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Medium to large labs (15+ computers), Windows domain</p>
				<h4>How it works:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Centralized management via Windows Server</li>
					<li>Group Policy Objects (GPOs) enforce restrictions</li>
					<li>User profiles stored on server</li>
					<li>Deploy software and updates centrally</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Cost:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Windows Server license: $500-1000</li>
					<li>Server hardware: $1000-3000</li>
					<li>Time investment: High initial setup</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Pros:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Centralized control and monitoring</li>
					<li>User accounts and roaming profiles</li>
					<li>Granular control over permissions</li>
					<li>Professional, scalable solution</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Cons:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Requires IT expertise</li>
					<li>Ongoing server maintenance</li>
					<li>Higher initial investment</li>
				</ul>
			</div>

			<div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border-2 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
				<h3>Strategy 3: Chromebooks (Managed)</h3>
				<p><strong>Best for:</strong> New deployments, education focus, cloud-based</p>
				<h4>How it works:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Chromebooks managed via Google Admin Console</li>
					<li>Automatic updates and security</li>
					<li>Powerwash returns to factory state</li>
					<li>Built-in content filtering options</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Cost:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Chromebooks: $200-400 each</li>
					<li>Chrome Education/Enterprise license: $30-50/device one-time</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Pros:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Low maintenance, automatic updates</li>
					<li>Secure by design</li>
					<li>Easy central management</li>
					<li>Cost-effective</li>
				</ul>
				<h4>Cons:</h4>
				<ul>
					<li>Limited to web-based apps</li>
					<li>Requires internet connection</li>
					<li>Less suitable for specialized software needs</li>
				</ul>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>üõ°Ô∏è Content Filtering for Workstations</h2>

		<h3>Approach 1: Network-Level Filtering (Recommended)</h3>
		<p>Filter at the router/firewall level (see our <a href="/guides/public-wifi-setup">Public WiFi Setup Guide</a>).</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Pros:</strong> Protects all devices, can't be bypassed, works on any OS</li>
			<li><strong>Cons:</strong> Same filtering for all computers, less granular</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Approach 2: Workstation-Level Filtering Software</h3>
		<p>Install filtering software on each computer for more control.</p>

		<div class="software-comparison">
			<h4>Recommended Software:</h4>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Qustodio for Schools:</strong> $5-8/device/year - Comprehensive, easy management</li>
				<li><strong>Net Nanny:</strong> $40/year per device - Good reporting, time limits</li>
				<li><strong>ContentKeeper:</strong> Enterprise pricing - School-focused, very robust</li>
				<li><strong>Covenant Eyes:</strong> $16/month for multiple devices - Faith-based, accountability focus</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<h3>Approach 3: Browser-Based Restrictions</h3>
		<p>For tighter budgets, use browser extensions and settings.</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Safe Search:</strong> Force SafeSearch on Google, Bing, YouTube</li>
			<li><strong>Browser extensions:</strong> BlockSite, uBlock Origin</li>
			<li><strong>Browser policies:</strong> Chrome/Edge can be managed via policy files</li>
			<li><strong>Limitations:</strong> Users can install different browsers if not locked down</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="alert alert-warning">
			<strong>Layered approach recommended:</strong> Combine network-level DNS filtering + workstation software + browser lockdown for maximum protection.
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>üîí Workstation Lockdown Strategies</h2>

		<h3>Windows Lockdown (Using Group Policy or Local Policy)</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Disable Control Panel:</strong> Prevent users from changing settings</li>
			<li><strong>Disable Command Prompt and PowerShell:</strong> Prevent script execution</li>
			<li><strong>Disable USB storage:</strong> Prevent malware via USB drives</li>
			<li><strong>Remove Run command:</strong> Prevent launching unauthorized programs</li>
			<li><strong>Hide drives:</strong> Only show necessary folders (Documents, Downloads)</li>
			<li><strong>Disable Task Manager:</strong> Prevent closing protection software</li>
			<li><strong>Software restriction policies:</strong> Only allow approved programs to run</li>
			<li><strong>Disable Windows Store:</strong> Prevent app installation</li>
			<li><strong>Redirect folders:</strong> Save all documents to network location</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>macOS Lockdown (Using Parental Controls or MDM)</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Managed user accounts:</strong> Standard accounts with restrictions</li>
			<li><strong>Limit applications:</strong> Only allow specific apps</li>
			<li><strong>Disable installation:</strong> Require admin password for new software</li>
			<li><strong>Content filtering:</strong> Built-in web content filter</li>
			<li><strong>Time limits:</strong> Set computer usage hours</li>
			<li><strong>Hide System Preferences:</strong> Prevent settings changes</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Creating Restricted User Accounts</h3>
		<ol>
			<li>Create "Public User" account with Standard (not Admin) privileges</li>
			<li>Set auto-login to Public User account</li>
			<li>Hide admin account from login screen</li>
			<li>Set complex admin password (keep secure)</li>
			<li>Configure restrictions on Public User account</li>
		</ol>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>‚è±Ô∏è Time Limit Management</h2>

		<h3>Why Time Limits Matter</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Prevents monopolization by one user</li>
			<li>Ensures fair access during peak times</li>
			<li>Encourages efficient use</li>
			<li>Reduces wear on equipment</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Implementation Options</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Honor system:</strong> Posted sign "30-minute limit when others waiting"
				<ul>
					<li>Pros: Free, simple</li>
					<li>Cons: Not enforced, relies on courtesy</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Timer software:</strong> UserLock, TimeCamp, EnforceStation
				<ul>
					<li>Pros: Automatic enforcement</li>
					<li>Cons: Cost $20-50/computer/year</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Windows Task Scheduler:</strong> Auto-restart after set time
				<ul>
					<li>Pros: Free, built-in</li>
					<li>Cons: Fixed schedule, not flexible</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Sign-up sheet:</strong> Reserve slots in advance
				<ul>
					<li>Pros: Organized, fair</li>
					<li>Cons: Requires staff oversight</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Recommended Time Limits</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Peak hours (after school, evenings):</strong> 30 minutes, can extend if no one waiting</li>
			<li><strong>Off-peak hours:</strong> 1 hour, can extend</li>
			<li><strong>Special circumstances:</strong> Job applications, important research - allow extensions</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>üñ®Ô∏è Printer Management</h2>

		<h3>Preventing Abuse</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Limit pages per session:</strong> 10-20 pages maximum</li>
			<li><strong>Require approval:</strong> Print job held until staff releases</li>
			<li><strong>Charge for printing:</strong> $0.10-0.25 per page (covers costs)</li>
			<li><strong>No color printing:</strong> Or charge premium for color</li>
			<li><strong>Monitor print queue:</strong> Review what's being printed</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Software Solutions</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>PaperCut:</strong> Track and control printing, charge if needed</li>
			<li><strong>PrinterLogic:</strong> Print management and auditing</li>
			<li><strong>Windows print quotas:</strong> Built-in per-user limits</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>üíæ Storage and USB Management</h2>

		<h3>Strategies</h3>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Disable USB ports:</strong> Prevent malware via flash drives
				<ul>
					<li>Group Policy: Disable USB storage but allow keyboards/mice</li>
					<li>Physical: Use USB port blockers ($1 each)</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Allow USB but scan:</strong> Antivirus auto-scans USB drives
				<ul>
					<li>Pros: More flexible</li>
					<li>Cons: Risk of infection</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Cloud storage only:</strong> Users save to Google Drive, OneDrive
				<ul>
					<li>Pros: No local storage needed, accessible anywhere</li>
					<li>Cons: Requires user accounts</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
			<li><strong>Network share:</strong> Users save to monitored network folder
				<ul>
					<li>Pros: Centralized, can review files</li>
					<li>Cons: Requires file server</li>
				</ul>
			</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="alert alert-warning">
			<strong>Privacy consideration:</strong> If allowing local storage, ensure Deep Freeze or similar wipes it between users. Sensitive documents left behind are a privacy violation.
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>üîß Maintenance & Updates</h2>

		<h3>Weekly Tasks</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Physical cleaning (keyboards, mice, screens)</li>
			<li>Check for physical damage</li>
			<li>Verify filtering is working</li>
			<li>Clear print queue</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Monthly Tasks</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Windows/macOS updates (if using Deep Freeze, thaw first)</li>
			<li>Antivirus definition updates</li>
			<li>Review usage logs and filtering reports</li>
			<li>Test all computers for functionality</li>
			<li>Update filtering software</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Quarterly Tasks</h3>
		<ul>
			<li>Deep clean (dust inside cases, clean vents)</li>
			<li>Check for failing hardware (slow computers, dying drives)</li>
			<li>Update software applications</li>
			<li>Review and update acceptable use policy</li>
			<li>Backup configurations</li>
		</ul>

		<h3>Update Strategy with Deep Freeze</h3>
		<ol>
			<li>Schedule maintenance window (early morning, late evening)</li>
			<li>"Thaw" Deep Freeze on all computers (allow changes)</li>
			<li>Run Windows Update</li>
			<li>Update antivirus, filtering software</li>
			<li>Test computer functionality</li>
			<li>"Freeze" Deep Freeze again</li>
			<li>Restart all computers</li>
		</ol>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>üìã Standard Operating Procedures</h2>

		<div class="sop-box">
			<h3>Opening Procedures</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Turn on all computers (if not left on)</li>
				<li>Verify all computers booted successfully</li>
				<li>Check that internet/filtering is working</li>
				<li>Ensure printers have paper and toner</li>
				<li>Post current time limits and policies</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>Closing Procedures</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>Ask all users to log off and save work</li>
				<li>Restart all computers (clears sessions, updates Deep Freeze)</li>
				<li>Check for damage or issues</li>
				<li>Clear printer queue</li>
				<li>Lock computer room if applicable</li>
			</ul>

			<h3>When User Reports Issue</h3>
			<ol>
				<li>Ask user to describe problem</li>
				<li>Try simple fix first (restart browser, log out/in)</li>
				<li>Check if filtering is blocking legitimate site (temporarily whitelist if needed)</li>
				<li>If hardware problem, mark computer "Out of Order" and log issue</li>
				<li>Move user to different computer if available</li>
				<li>Document recurring issues for IT review</li>
			</ol>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
		<h2>‚ö†Ô∏è Common Challenges & Solutions</h2>

		<div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border-2 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
			<h3>Challenge: Users installing unauthorized software</h3>
			<p><strong>Solutions:</strong></p>
			<ul>
				<li>Use Standard user accounts (not Admin)</li>
				<li>Software restriction policies (whitelist only approved apps)</li>
				<li>Deep Freeze removes installations on reboot</li>
				<li>If legitimate need, install software during maintenance and freeze it</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border-2 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
			<h3>Challenge: Users bypassing filtering</h3>
			<p><strong>Solutions:</strong></p>
			<ul>
				<li>Block VPN apps and services at firewall level</li>
				<li>Disable browser installation (lock to pre-configured browsers)</li>
				<li>Use DNS filtering at network level (can't bypass)</li>
				<li>Monitor for proxy sites and add to blocklist</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border-2 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
			<h3>Challenge: Computers slowing down over time</h3>
			<p><strong>Solutions:</strong></p>
			<ul>
				<li>Deep Freeze prevents permanent slowdown</li>
				<li>Regular restarts clear temporary files</li>
				<li>Limit browser extensions to essentials</li>
				<li>Upgrade RAM if computers have less than 8GB</li>
				<li>Consider SSD upgrades for older machines</li>
			</ul>
		</div>

		<div class="bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800 border-2 border-blue-200 dark:border-blue-700 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
			<h3>Challenge: Malware infections</h3>
			<p><strong>Prevention:</strong></p>
			<ul>
				<li>Deep Freeze removes malware on restart</li>
				<li>Keep antivirus updated and running real-time scans</li>
				<li>Block USB storage or scan automatically</li>
				<li>User education about not clicking suspicious links</li>
				<li>Network-level filtering blocks malicious sites</li>
			</ul>
		</div>
	</section>

	<section>
